{"title_page": "Blunt Force Trauma (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name =Blunt Force Trauma\n| image =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| film name =\n| director =Ken Sanzel\n| producer ={{Plainlist|\n*Eric Brenner\n* Melina Lizette\n* Rich Mento\n* Gary Preisler\n}}\n| writer =Ken Sanzel\n| screenplay =\n| story =\n| based on = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} -->\n| narrator =\n| starring ={{Plainlist|\n*[[Mickey Rourke]]\n*[[Freida Pinto]]\n*[[Ryan Kwanten]]\n}}\n| music =[[Darren Jackson (musician)|Darren Jackson]]\n| cinematography =Paulo Andr\u00e9s P\u00e9rez\n| editing =Matt Mayer\n| studio =ETA Films\n| distributor = [[Voltage Pictures]] (US)\n| released = {{Film date|2015|07|20|US}}\n| runtime = 95 minutes\n| country =Colombia\nUnited States\n| language =\n| budget =\n| gross =\n}}\n'''''Blunt Force Trauma''''' is a 2015 American-Colombian English-language [[action film]] directed by Ken Sanzel and starring [[Mickey Rourke]], [[Freida Pinto]], and [[Ryan Kwanten]].\n\n==Premise==\nPinto plays a girl looking for her brother's killer. The film is  based on a banned shooting game.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Mickey Rourke]] as  Zorringer\n*[[Freida Pinto]] as Colt\n*[[Ryan Kwanten]] as John\n\n==Production==\nPrincipal photography was done entirely in [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia in 2014. In North America, Alchemy will be the film's distributor. It competed in the [[Woodstock Film Festival]] and the [[Montreal World Film Festival]].<ref name=PMC>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Ryan Kwanten\u2019s \u2018Blunt Force Trauma\u2019 Sells to Alchemy for North America|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/ryan-kwanten-blunt-force-trauma-alchemy-1201604847/|accessdate=October 2, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref name=THR>{{cite news|last1=DeFore|first1=John|title='Blunt Force Trauma': Montreal Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/blunt-force-trauma-montreal-review-820902|accessdate=October 2, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nJohn DeFore of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' criticized the film, stating that it \"takes itself much more seriously than viewers will.\"<ref name=THR />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|3520290}}\n\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Colombia]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Colombian films]]\n[[Category:Colombian action films]]\n[[Category:Colombian drama films]]\n\n\n{{2010s-action-film-stub}}\n{{Colombia-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name =Blunt Force Trauma\n| image =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| film name =\n| director =Ken Sanzel\n| producer ={{Plainlist|\n*Eric Brenner\n* Melina Lizette\n* Rich Mento\n* Gary Preisler\n}}\n| writer =Ken Sanzel\n| screenplay =\n| story =\n| based on = <!-- {{based on|title of the original work|writer of the original work}} -->\n| narrator =\n| starring ={{Plainlist|\n*[[Mickey Rourke]]\n*[[Freida Pinto]]\n*[[Ryan Kwanten]]\n}}\n| music =[[Darren Jackson (musician)|Darren Jackson]]\n| cinematography =Paulo Andr\u00e9s P\u00e9rez\n| editing =Matt Mayer\n| studio =ETA Films\n| distributor = [[Voltage Pictures]] (US)\n| released = {{Film date|2015|07|20|US}}\n| runtime = 95 minutes\n| country =Colombia\nUnited States\n| language =\n| budget =\n| gross =\n}}\n'''''Blunt Force Trauma''''' is a 2015 American-Colombian English-language [[action film]] directed by Ken Sanzel and starring [[Mickey Rourke]], [[Freida Pinto]] and [[Ryan Kwanten]].\n\n==Premise==\nPinto plays a girl looking for her brother's killer. The film is  based on a banned shooting game.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Mickey Rourke]] as  Zorringer\n*[[Freida Pinto]] as Colt\n*[[Ryan Kwanten]] as John\n\n==Production==\nPrincipal photography was done entirely in [[Bogot\u00e1]], Colombia in 2014. In North America, Alchemy will be the film's distributor. It competed in the [[Woodstock Film Festival]] and the [[Montreal World Film Festival]].<ref name=PMC>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Ryan Kwanten\u2019s \u2018Blunt Force Trauma\u2019 Sells to Alchemy for North America|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/ryan-kwanten-blunt-force-trauma-alchemy-1201604847/|accessdate=October 2, 2015|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=September 29, 2015}}</ref><ref name=THR>{{cite news|last1=DeFore|first1=John|title='Blunt Force Trauma': Montreal Review|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/blunt-force-trauma-montreal-review-820902|accessdate=October 2, 2015|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|date=September 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nJohn DeFore of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' criticized the film, stating that it \"takes itself much more seriously than viewers will.\"<ref name=THR />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|3520290}}\n\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Colombia]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Colombian films]]\n[[Category:Colombian action films]]\n[[Category:Colombian drama films]]\n\n\n{{2010s-action-film-stub}}\n{{Colombia-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Freeknowledgecreator", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blunt_Force_Trauma_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Marie Takvam", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Marie Takvam\n| image = Marie Takvam.jpg\n| caption = Takvam in 1965\n| birth_name = Marie Skylstad\n| birth_date = {{Birth date |1926|12|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[\u00d8rsta]], Norway\n| death_date = {{Death date and age |2008|1|28|1926|12|5|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = Norwegian\n| other_names = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = poet, children's writer, novelist, playwright and actress\n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| home_town = \n| television = \n| religion = \n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = [[Magnus Takvam]]\n| parents = \n| relatives =\n| awards = \n}}\n\n'''Marie Takvam''' (n\u00e9e Skylstad; December 5, 1926 &ndash; January 28, 2008) was a Norwegian poet, novelist, writer of children's books, playwright and actress. \n<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Marie Takvam |first= |last= |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |editor-last=Godal | editor-first=Anne Marit | editor-link=Anne Marit Godal |publisher=Norsk nettleksikon |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Marie_Takvam |language=Norwegian|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nShe was born at [[\u00d8rsta]] in [[M\u00f8re og Romsdal]], Norway.  Her parents were Johan Skylstad (1883-1974) and Martha Sperre (1901-1983).\nShe grew up at [[Hj\u00f8rundfjord]] in [[Sunnm\u00f8re]] as the eldest of five siblings of a farm family. After graduation [[artium]] at [[Nordfjordeid]] in 1945, she moved to [[Oslo]] together with her future husband Johannes Takvam  (1925-2003).  They were married during 1950; their  marriage dissolved in 1975. Takvam studied psychology at the [[University of Oslo]], but had to cancel her studies when her eldest son was born. She was the mother of  journalist [[Magnus Takvam]].\n<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Marie Takvam |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Gudrun |last=Sylte |authorlink= |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Marie_Takvam/utdypning |language=Norwegian |accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =  https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/wiki/Marie_Takvam|title= Marie Takvam|publisher =lokalhistoriewik |accessdate= April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTakvam worked in the 1950s and 1960s as program leader for the children's programming at [[NRK]].\nShe published 12 poetry collections over a 45-year period. She made her literary debut in 1952 with the poetry collection ''D\u00e5p under sju stjerner''.<ref name=nrk>[http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/kultur/forfattere/1475791.html Profile: \"Takvam, Marie\"] &ndash; ''nrk.no litteratur''  (Retrieved on January 29, 2008)</ref> Among her other collections are ''Merke etter liv'' from 1962, ''Br\u00f8d og tran'' from 1969, and ''Falle og reise seg att'' from 1980.<ref>{{cite web\n|url =  https://www.allkunne.no/framside/biografiar/t/marie-takvam/103/10190/Takvam |title= Marie Takvam |publisher =Allkunne|author= \u00d8ystein Espe Bae\n|date=  February 7, 2018|accessdate= April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMarie Takvam was awarded several literary  including the [[Dobloug Prize]] in 1983, and the [[Nynorsk Literature Prize]] in 1997 and [[Melsomprisen]] in 1998.\nShe died during 2008 at Ljabruhjemmet in Oslo and was buried at [[Vestre gravlund]].\n<ref name=nbl/><ref name=prizes>[http://www.barum.folkebibl.no/utiverden/litteraturpris/norden.html \"Nordiske priser\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024111348/http://www.barum.folkebibl.no/utiverden/litteraturpris/norden.html |date=October 24, 2007 }}  (Retrieved on January 29, 2008)</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''D\u00e5p under sju stjerner'', 1952\n* ''Syngjande kjelder'', 1954\n* ''Merke etter liv'', 1962\n* ''Mosaikk i lys'', 1965\n* ''Br\u00f8d og tran'', 1969\n* ''Auger, hender'', 1975\n* ''Dansaren'', 1975\n* ''Falle og reise seg att'', 1980\n* ''Brevet fr\u00e5 Alexandra'', 1981\n* ''Aldrande drabantby'', 1987\n* ''Rogneb\u00e6r'', 1990\n* ''Dikt i samling'', 1997\n\n==Filmography==\n<ref name=imdb>[https://akas.imdb.com/name/nm0847740/ \"Marie Takvam\"] &ndash; ''Internet Movie Database'' (Retrieved on January 29, 2008)</ref>\n* ''\u00c5penbaringen'' (1977)\n* ''Det tause flertall'' (1977)\n* ''Hvem har bestemt?'' (1978)\n* ''[[Betrayal (1981 film)|L\u00f8perjenten]]'' (1981)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{Dobloug Prize winners|state =collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Takvam, Marie}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from M\u00f8re og Romsdal]]\n[[Category:University of Oslo alumni]]\n[[Category:Norwegian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian women novelists]]\n[[Category:Norwegian film actresses]]\n[[Category:Women children's writers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian women dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Norwegian women poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian poets]]\n[[Category:Dobloug Prize winners]]\n[[Category:Burials at Vestre gravlund]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Marie Takvam\n| image = Marie Takvam.jpg\n| caption = Takvam in 1965\n| birth_name = Marie Skylstad\n| birth_date = {{Birth date |1926|12|5|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[\u00d8rsta]], Norway\n| death_date = {{Death date and age |2008|1|28|1926|12|5|df=y}}\n| death_place = \n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = Norwegian\n| other_names = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = poet, children's writer, novelist, playwright and actress\n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| home_town = \n| television = \n| religion = \n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = [[Magnus Takvam]]\n| parents = \n| relatives =\n| awards = \n}}\n\n'''Marie Takvam''' (n\u00e9e Skylstad; December 5, 1926 &ndash; January 28, 2008) was a Norwegian poet, novelist, writer of children's books, playwright and actress. \n<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Marie Takvam |first= |last= |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |editor-last=Godal | editor-first=Anne Marit | editor-link=Anne Marit Godal |publisher=Norsk nettleksikon |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Marie_Takvam |language=Norwegian|accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nShe was born at [[\u00d8rsta]] in [[M\u00f8re og Romsdal]], Norway.  Her parents were Johan Skylstad (1883-1974) and Martha Sperre (1901-1983).\nShe grew up at [[Hj\u00f8rundfjord]] in [[Sunnm\u00f8re]] as the eldest of five siblings of a farm family. After graduation [[artium]] at [[Nordfjordeid]] in 1945, she moved to [[Oslo]] together with her future husband Johannes Takvam  (1925-2003).  They were married during 1950; their  marriage dissolved in 1975. Takvam studied psychology at the [[University of Oslo]], but had to cancel her studies when her eldest son was born. She was the mother of  journalist [[Magnus Takvam]].\n<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Marie Takvam |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Gudrun |last=Sylte |authorlink= |editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Marie_Takvam/utdypning |language=Norwegian |accessdate=16 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =  https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/wiki/Marie_Takvam|title= Marie Takvam|publisher =lokalhistoriewik |accessdate= April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTakvam worked in the 1950s and 1960s as program leader for the children's programming at [[NRK]].\nShe published 12 poetry collections over a 45-year period. She made her literary debut in 1952 with the poetry collection ''D\u00e5p under sju stjerner''.<ref name=nrk>[http://www.nrk.no/nyheter/kultur/forfattere/1475791.html Profile: \"Takvam, Marie\"] &ndash; ''nrk.no litteratur''  (Retrieved on January 29, 2008)</ref> Among her other collections are ''Merke etter liv'' from 1962, ''Br\u00f8d og tran'' from 1969, and ''Falle og reise seg att'' from 1980.<ref>{{cite web\n|url =  https://www.allkunne.no/framside/biografiar/t/marie-takvam/103/10190/Takvam |title= Marie Takvam |publisher =Allkunne|author= \u00d8ystein Espe Bae\n|date=  February 7, 2018|accessdate= April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nMarie Takvam was awarded several literary  including the [[Dobloug Prize]] in 1983, and the [[Nynorsk Literature Prize]] in 1997 and [[Melsomprisen]] in 1998.\nShe died during 2008 at Ljabruhjemmet in Oslo and was buried at [[Vestre gravlund]].\n<ref name=nbl/><ref name=prizes>[http://www.barum.folkebibl.no/utiverden/litteraturpris/norden.html \"Nordiske priser\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071024111348/http://www.barum.folkebibl.no/utiverden/litteraturpris/norden.html |date=October 24, 2007 }}  (Retrieved on January 29, 2008)</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''D\u00e5p under sju stjerner'', 1952\n* ''Syngjande kjelder'', 1954\n* ''Merke etter liv'', 1962\n* ''Mosaikk i lys'', 1965\n* ''Br\u00f8d og tran'', 1969\n* ''Auger, hender'', 1975\n* ''Dansaren'', 1975\n* ''Falle og reise seg att'', 1980\n* ''Brevet fr\u00e5 Alexandra'', 1981\n* ''Aldrande drabantby'', 1987\n* ''Rogneb\u00e6r'', 1990\n* ''Dikt i samling'', 1997\n\n==Filmography==\n<ref name=imdb>[https://akas.imdb.com/name/nm0847740/ \"Marie Takvam\"] &ndash; ''Internet Movie Database'' (Retrieved on January 29, 2008)</ref>\n* ''\u00c5penbaringen'' (1977)\n* ''Det tause flertall'' (1977)\n* ''Hvem har bestemt?'' (1978)\n* ''[[Betrayal (1981 film)|L\u00f8perjenten]]'' (1981)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\